Hi,
We are ChildLikE,inc., an up and coming non-profit based in the Dallas,Texas Metropolitan area, geared towards
educating youth on matters relating to 3D Printing and Robotics. We provide a technological literacy which is
unavailable to most children around the United States, and we do it with hands-on training geared towards real-world
application. In our development of new educational tools fitted for the Technological Era, we are playing our part in
what we see as the inevitable integration of robotics and 3D printing with education, and we hope to swiftly pull such
advances into the sphere of public education.
While currently operating as a stand-alone business, we have reached out to the local community and are building a
base of support, a network for innovation in the area of after-school programs and community learning. A major goal
of ChildLikE,inc. is to provide skills and understandings which offer an advantage in today's world of technology,
particularly to kids in struggling neighborhoods, many of whom only have sports or music as outlets and as avenues
for escaping from their economic environment. We aim to teach kids to build and program the kinds of devices so
ubiquitously in use today.
Thank you for your time,
ChildLikE,inc.

bio:
It has always been my motto that "you can learn anything, so why not do everything?". So I have become a jack of all trades.

I started 3D modeling at the age of 15 with Ray Dream Studio (now Carrara), Bryce 3D and Poser. I soon found myself with a Graphic Design job for 15 years, making catalogs, posters, fliers, banners, convention booths (I had access to, and learned, 3D Studio Max) jewelry pins, etc. I then moved into IT, servers, networking and programming.

3D printing started more as a hobby for modifying my RC cars, but quickly became useful with work situations (TV screens with incompatible mounting setups).

I can only imagine how people must have felt 50 years ago when their parents bought the first washing machine and the whole family sat down in front of the washing machine to look through that tiny circular window, how clothes spin and the soap foams..

Hoover's history reaches back more than 100 years and traces a path to the very invention of the vacuum itself. In 1907, janitor Murray Spangler saw a problem that needed fixing: In the course of his daily work, he encountered dust that triggered asthma attacks. Working at night, Spangler devised a "suction sweeper" to pull dust and dirt out of the air and off the ground. W. H. Hoover bought Spangler's patent in 1908, and began selling the country's first sweepers to the public. It was the beginning of more than a century of innovations, from our famous beater bar to disposable paper vacuum bags, vacuum cleaner headlights and self-propelling technology and even the side-mounted hose. Today, Hoover continues to build on its history of innovation and creating effortless cleaning solutions.
